Of course you can “dog-groom” it by dividing by $1-i$. $$\\~\\ \frac{i\left(1-i^{259}\right)}{1-i}$$ [/think] \\~\\ Since $i^{4n+1}=i$, we have $i^{259}=i$, and so the above becomes $\\\frac{-i\left(1+i\right)}{1-i}\\=\frac{-2i}{1-i}\\=\frac{-2i\left(1+i\right)}{\left(1-i\right)\left(1+i\right)}\\=\frac{i-2}{2}$ [/think] Finally, you can rationalize the denominator to get $\dfrac{2-i}{2}$ [/answer]
Let's paste the code for this MathJax solution below:

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}
\begin{align*}
&\text{User: } \text{Compute } i + i^2 + i^3 + \cdots + i^{258} + i^{259}.\\[-2.5cm]
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
&\text{Assistant: } \text{Of course you can “dog-groom” it by dividing by } 1-i.\\[-2.5cm]
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
&\text{After rationalizing the denominator, we get }\frac{2-i}{2}.\\[-2.5cm]
\end{align*}

\end{document}
from sympy import I, simplify

# Compute the sum i + i^2 + i^3 + ... + i^258 + i^259
i = I
n = 259
sum_of_powers = sum(i**k for k in range(1, n+1))

# Simplify the result
result = simplify(sum_of_powers)

# Display the result
print(result)
